# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockchain-settlement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] This allows brokers and financial companies to hold their securities at one location where they can be available for clearing and settlement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] In recent decades this has usually been finished electronically, making it much faster and easier than was traditionally the case where physical certificates had to be exchanged after a trade had been completed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] In some cases these organizations also carry out centralized comparison and transaction processing such as clearing and settlement of securities transfers, securities pledges, and securities freezes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] In modern corporate debt markets, investors achieve collateralization through CSDs.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The CSDs operate as trustees for the owners of the security whereby the collateral is stored and automatically transferred to the lenders in case of non-performance.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The first recorded CSD was the Wiener Giro- und Cassen-Verein in Vienna, established in 1872.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] Also in 1872, the Berliner Kassenverein introduced a CSD-like service (German: *Giro-Effekten-Depots*), discontinued it two years later, and revived it on a permanent basis in 1882.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] Similarly named *Kassenverein* institutions subsequently spread in Germany, and under the German occupation of France, also to France in the early 1940s.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The United States adopted the CSD model with the creation of the Depository Trust Company in 1973 following coordinated initiatives of the financial industry in the late 1960s.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] In the United Kingdom, the CREST project was only initiated in 1993, leading to the 1996 creation of CRESTCo as the country's first CSD.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The development of the eurobond market in the 1960s led to the first so-called international CSD or ICSD in the form of the Euroclear System initially developed by the Morgan Guaranty branch in Brussels, started in 1968 and reorganized in late 2000 as Euroclear Bank.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] In reaction, a group of other banks in 1970 founded a competing entity in nearby Luxembourg, initially called Cedel and rebranded in 2000 as Clearstream Banking SA.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] At least initially, Euroclear was viewed as largely aligned with buy side interests whereas Cedel was closer to the sell side.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] A CSD can be national or international in nature, and may be for a specific type of security, such as government bonds.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] Many countries have one domestic CSD that was traditionally associated with the national stock exchange.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] These organizations are typically heavily regulated by the government and may or may not be separate from the exchanges where trading in securities occurs.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] An international CSD is a central securities depository that settles trades in international securities such as eurobonds although many also settle trades in various domestic securities, usually through direct or indirect (through local agents) links to local CSDs.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] Examples of international CSDs include Clearstream Banking SA (previously Cedel), Euroclear Bank, and SIX SIS.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] While viewed as a national CSD rather than an ICSD, the US Depository Trust Company (DTC) does hold over $2 trillion in non-US securities and in American depositary receipts from over 100 nations.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] However, there are risks and responsibilities regarding these services that must be taken into consideration in analyzing and evaluating each market on a case-by-case basis.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] CSDs have formed five regional associative bodies with partly overlapping membership: for example, the Central Securities Depository of Turkey (Turkish: *Merkezi Kayıt Kuruluşu*, MKK) is an associate member of ECSDA and a full member of ACG, AECSD and AMEDA.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The five associations, in turn, have formed a global body, the World Forum of Central Securities Depositories.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The European Central Securities Depositories Association (ECSDA), based in Brussels, was established in November 1997 by 13 founding members.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] As of early 2025, ECSDA had 32 full members and 8 associate members.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The Asia-Pacific Central Securities Depository Group, or Asia-Pacific CSD Group (ACG), was also formed in November 1997.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] As of early 2025, its membership was as follows.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] In addition, the ACG had five associate members: the Association of Global Custodians, Calastone, the Singapore branch of Deutsche Bank, HSBC Hong Kong, and SIX SIS Singapore.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The Americas Central Securities Depositories Association (ACSDA, Spanish: *Asociación de Depósitos Centrales de Valores de América*) was formed in 1999, with headquarters in Lima.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The Association of Eurasian Central Securities Depositories (AECSD) brings together a number of central securities depositories (CSDs) in 9 countries of the former Soviet Union as well as India, Indonesia, Iran, Mongolia, South Korea, and Turkey.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] It was formed in Moscow in 2004, following a series of gathering of its would-be members in the previous three years.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The Africa & Middle East Depositories Association (AMEDA) was established in April 2005.
[src:blockchain-settlement/central-securities-depository] The World Forum of Central Securities Depositories, or World Forum of CSDs, brings together the ECSDA, ACG, ACSDA, AECSD, and AMEDA.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] A **distributed ledger** (also called a **shared ledger** or **distributed ledger technology** or **DLT**) is a system whereby replicated, shared, and synchronized digital data is geographically spread (distributed) across many sites, countries, or institutions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] In contrast to a centralized database, a distributed ledger does not require a central administrator, and consequently does not have a single (central) point-of-failure.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] In general, a distributed ledger requires a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network and consensus algorithms so that the ledger is reliably replicated across distributed computer nodes (servers, clients, etc.).
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] The most common form of distributed ledger technology is the blockchain (commonly associated with cryptocurrency), which can either be on a public or private network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Infrastructure for data management is a common barrier to implementing DLT.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Distributed ledger data is typically spread across multiple nodes (computational devices) on a P2P network, where each replicates and saves an identical copy of the ledger data and updates itself independently of other nodes.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] The primary advantage of this distributed processing pattern is the lack of a central authority, which would constitute a single point of failure.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] When a ledger update transaction is broadcast to the P2P network, each distributed node processes a new update transaction independently, and then collectively all working nodes use a consensus algorithm to determine the correct copy of the updated ledger.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Once a consensus has been determined, all the other nodes update themselves with the latest, correct copy of the updated ledger.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Security is enforced through cryptographic keys and signatures.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Certificate Transparency is an Internet security standard for monitoring and auditing the issuance of digital certificates based on a distributed ledger.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] It was initiated in 2011, standardised in 2013 and started to be used by the Google Chrome browser for all certificates in 2018.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] In 2016, some banks tested distributed ledger systems for payments to determine their usefulness.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] In 2020, Axoni launched Veris, a distributed ledger platform that manages equity swap transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] The platform, which matches and reconciles post-trade data on stock swaps, is used by BlackRock Inc., Goldman Sachs Group Inc., and Citigroup, Inc.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] A pilot scheme by the Monetary Authority of Singapore completed its first live trades using DLT in 2022.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] The pilot by Singapore's central bank involved JP Morgan, SBI Digital Asset Holdings and DBS.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] The banks traded using smart contracts against liquidity pools of tokenized Singapore government bonds, Japanese government bonds, yen, and Singapore dollars.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Standard Chartered Bank is exploring tokens for trade finance; and HSBC and United Overseas Bank are working with Marketnode, a digital markets infrastructure provider, on products for wealth management.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] DLT can be used for smart contracting, which is the formation of contracts which automatically complete when triggered by prevailing conditions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] DLT is itself secured by cryptographic methods, but can also be used as a base layer on which to build further cryptographic applications, such as protocols that require or benefit from a public broadcast mechanism, including transparent decryption.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] In the context of cryptocurrencies, distributed ledger technologies can be categorized in terms of their data structures, consensus algorithms, permissions, and whether they are mined.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] DLT data structure types include linear data structures (blockchains) to more complex directed acyclic graph (DAG) and hybrid data structures.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] DLT consensus algorithm types include proof-of-work (PoW) and proof-of-stake (PoS) algorithms and DAG consensus-building and voting algorithms.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] DLTs are generally either permissioned (private) or permissionless (public).
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] PoW cryptocurrencies are generally either 'mined' or 'non-mined', where the latter typically indicates 'pre-mined' cryptocurrencies, such as XRP or IOTA.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] PoS cryptocurrencies do not use miners, instead usually relying on validation among owners of the cryptocurrency, such as Cardano or Solana.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Blockchains are the most common DLT type, with a 256-bit secure hash algorithm (SHA).
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] DLTs based on DAG data structures or hybrid blockchain-DAG decrease transaction data size and transaction costs, while increasing transaction speeds compared with bitcoin, the first cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Examples of DAG DLT cryptocurrencies include MIOTA (IOTA Tangle DLT) and HBAR (Hedera Hashgraph).
[src:blockchain-settlement/distributed-ledger] Holochain represents a departure from traditional DLT models, using an agent-centric approach with individual source chains and a distributed hash table (DHT) for data validation, eliminating the need for a global consensus mechanism.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:blockchain-settlement/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In the context of securities, settlement involves their delivery to the beneficiary, usually against (in simultaneous exchange for) payment of money, to fulfill contractual obligations, such as those arising under securities trades.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Nowadays, settlement typically takes place in a central securities depository.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In the United States, the settlement date for marketable stocks is usually 1 business day after the trade is executed, often referred to as "T+1." For listed options and government securities in the US, settlement typically occurs 1 day after trade execution.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In Europe, settlement date has been adopted as 2 business days after the trade is executed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] As part of performance on the delivery obligations entailed by the trade, settlement involves the delivery of securities and the corresponding payment.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] A number of risks arise for the parties during the settlement interval, which are managed by the process of clearing, which follows trading and precedes settlement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Clearing involves modifying those contractual obligations so as to facilitate settlement, often by netting and novation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Settlement involves the delivery of securities from one party to another.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Delivery usually takes place against payment known as delivery versus payment, but some deliveries are made without a corresponding payment (sometimes referred to as a *free delivery*, *free of payment* or *FOP* delivery, or in the United States, *delivery versus free*).
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Examples of a delivery without payment are the delivery of securities collateral against a loan of securities, and a delivery made pursuant to a margin call.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Prior to modern financial market technologies and methods such as depositories and securities held in electronic form, securities settlement involved the physical movement of paper instruments, or certificates and transfer forms.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Payment was usually made by paper cheque upon receipt by the registrar or transfer agent of properly negotiated certificates and other requisite documents.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Physical/paper settlement involves higher risks, inasmuch as paper instruments, certificates, and transfer forms are subject to risks electronic media are not, such as loss, theft, clerical errors, and forgery (see indirect holding system).
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In the United Kingdom, the weakness of paper-based settlement was exposed by a programme of privatisation of nationalised industries in the 1980s, and the Big Bang of 1986 led to an explosion in the volume of trades, and settlement delays became significant.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In the market crash of 1987, many investors sought to limit their losses by selling their securities, but found that the failure of timely settlement left them exposed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The electronic settlement system came about largely as a result of *Clearance and Settlement Systems in the World's Securities Markets*, a report in 1989 by the Washington-based think tank, the Group of Thirty.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] This report made nine recommendations with a view to achieving more efficient settlement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] This was followed up in 2003 with a report, *Clearing and Settlement: A Plan of Action*, with twenty recommendations.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In an electronic settlement system, electronic settlement takes place between participants.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] If a non-participant wishes to settle its interests, it must do so through a participant acting as a custodian.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The interests of participants are recorded by credit entries in securities accounts maintained in their names by the operator of the system.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] It permits both quick and efficient settlement by removing the need for paperwork, and the simultaneous delivery of securities with the payment of a corresponding cash sum (called delivery versus payment, or DVP) in the agreed upon currency.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] After the trade and before settlement, the rights of the purchaser are contractual and therefore personal.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Because they are merely personal, the purchaser's rights are at risk in the event of the insolvency of the vendor.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] After settlement, the purchaser owns securities and his rights are proprietary.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Settlement is the delivery of securities to complete trades.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] It involves upgrading personal rights into property rights and thus protects market participants from the risk of the default of their counterparties.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Immobilisation and dematerialisation are the two broad goals of electronic settlement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Immobilisation entails the use of securities in paper form and the use of a central securities depository or more than one, which is/are electronically linked to a settlement system.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Securities (either constituted by paper instruments or represented by paper certificates) are immobilised in the sense that they are held by the depository at all times.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In the transition from paper-based to electronic practice, immoblisation often serves as a transitional phase prior to dematerialisation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The Depository Trust Company in New York is the largest immobilizer of securities in the world.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Euroclear Bank and Clearstream Banking SA are two examples of international immobilisation systems.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Both originally settled eurobonds, but now a wide range of international securities are settled through them including many types of sovereign debt and equity securities.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Dematerialisation involves dispensing with paper instruments and certificates altogether.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Dematerialised securities exist only in the form of electronic records.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The legal impact of dematerialisation differs in relation to bearer and registered securities respectively.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In a direct holding system, participants hold the underlying securities directly.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The settlement system does not stand in the chain of ownership, but merely serves as a conduit for communications of participants to issuers.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The terms *T+1*, *T+2*, etc., are a shorthand for "trade date plus one day", "trade date plus two days", etc., indicating how many business days after a security transaction occurs that the trade must be settled.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Rules or customs in financial markets for securities transactions provide for this 'settlement period', which is the mandated time for official transfer of securities to the buyer's account and the cash to seller's account.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The most common current settlement period for securities transactions is one business day after the day of a transaction, which is abbreviated to T+1.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] On settlement, the seller must produce the security's certificate and executed share transfer form in exchange for payment from the purchaser.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Many countries now dispense with the requirement that a physical stock certificate be produced, a process known as dematerialization, and have adopted electronic settlement systems.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Similarly, T+2 means the previous convention of trade date plus two days, T+3 means three days, etc.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] During the 1700s the Amsterdam Stock Exchange had close links with the London Stock Exchange and they would often list each other's stocks.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] To clear the trades, time was required for the physical stock certificate or cash to move from Amsterdam to London and back.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] This led to a standard settlement period of 14 days which was the time it usually took for a courier to make the journey on horseback and by ship.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Most exchanges continued to use the same model over the next few hundred years.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Settlement procedures varied considerably across national stock markets.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] There were two main types of settlement period used by different countries, either a fixed number of days after the transaction known as *fixed settlement lag* or periodically on a fixed date when all transactions up to that date are settled known as *fixed settlement date*.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In France, Italy, and, to some extent, Switzerland and Belgium, as well as some developing countries, the settlement of all transactions took place once a month on a fixed date.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The last day of trading on which all trades are settled was called the liquidation.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The liquidation took place on the seventh business day preceding the end of the calendar month.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In the United States, the New York Stock Exchange used T+1 in the 1920s, and the American Stock Exchange used T+2 prior to 1953.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] These settlement periods were gradually extended to T+5 by the late 1960s as brokerage firms became overwhelmed by the massive volume of securities transactions paperwork awaiting settlement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The Black Monday (1987) stock market crash prompted a move to reduce settlement times.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Settlement dates in most exchanges reduced to three days (T+3).
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] In 2017, the move by most stock exchanges was towards adoption of T+2 (trade date plus two days).
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] For example, the United Kingdom adopted T+2 in October 2014 and the United States adopted T+2 in September 2017.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Indian stock exchanges planned a move to T+1 starting in 2022.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The US and Canada targeted a transition to T+1 early in 2024.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Canada adopted T+1 beginning on May 27, 2024, as did Argentina, Jamaica, Mexico, and the US on the following day.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Chile, Colombia, and Peru are slated to move to T+1 in 2025, and ESMA recommended the EU transition to T+1 on October 11, 2027.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Under a one-day settlement rule (T+1), settlement occurs on the business day following the transaction date.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Saturday, Sunday and public holidays are not market business days.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] For example, if a transaction occurs on a Friday, the payment or check must arrive at the broker's office by the close of business on Monday, unless a public holiday delays the settlement day.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The rationale for the delayed settlement is to give time for the seller to get documents to the settlement and for the purchaser to clear the funds required for settlement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] The one-day settlement period (T+1) applies to most security transactions, including stocks, bonds, municipal securities, mutual funds traded through a brokerage firm, and limited partnerships that trade on an exchange.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Two-day settlement has been the convention in the off-exchange foreign exchange market well before exchanges moved to this convention.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Government securities, stock options, and options on futures contracts settle on the next business day following the trade or T+1.
[src:blockchain-settlement/settlement-finance] Futures contracts themselves settle the day of the trade.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:blockchain-settlement/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
